properties.about me:
A thatched hut, no electricity, very few material possessions, and life was a bit wet during the monsoon seasons, water dripping through the thatched roof, frogs singing all night, and the sound of thunder and the bright flashlight of the lightning. Other seasons, the nearby river was beautiful, the clear sky filled with millions of stars, some late evenings illuminated with fireflies, which we were told, are the souls of our caring ancestors. Bright sunrise and sad deep ever changing sunsets - nature was my soul mate. Schooling was a pain.I dreamt in colors and patterns and never in words. I started drawing at a very young age and my artistic talents somehow got accepted in school!I better give a brief sketch of Kerala, my home province. We may have been poor, but we had our village libraries, a from where I managed to read books - translations of classics like Le Miserables,Crime and Punishment, Brothers Karamazov and Malayalam modern classics.It is this combination of unpolluted natural environment and aptitude for drawings and a nostalgia for my childhood visuals in my current realities of urban landscapes that make me what I am now. This perhaps, sums up my art.

Animate & Create is an animation workshop company aimed at giving young people the chance to get their ideas across through animation. Our intention is to empower young people, giving them control to present their opinions whilst having fun and getting creative with film-making.

The workshops are extremely hands-on and help to educate whilst making the process of learning more enjoyable. During our workshops young people have the chance to write scripts, make models and sets, animate characters and watch their films back after the process on the big screen. Workshops have a range of positive outcomes for young people, including planning and communication skills, developing group work and building self confidence. The workshops also introduce new technical skills through working with digital media, including cameras and ICT equipment.

properties.media interests: I have grown to value media technology as a tool in the process for social change and not just a “magic bean” product. I have seen technology centers, along with other non-profits, fail to holistically approach integrating technology into their programs or allocate enough resources and time to weave technology into the context of their daily operations. The adults and youth in my recent new media workshops are not only often surprised at how easy it is to create the media but also that their voice might matter in a larger conversation. To fight this ignorance, I continue to teach workshops in blogging and digital storytelling in community technology centers and after-school programs, as well as with my fellow VISTAs, literacy educators, and public access producers. I often present new media and technology fluency as both a persuasive and accessible skill as I search for practical solutions to issues of urban planning, public policy, and community development.
properties.organization name: Intel Computer Clubhouse Network (Museum of Science, Boston)
properties.about me:
I support organizational adoption of participatory media and digital storytelling tools for community organizing and youth development goals.  You might remember me as the coordinator at the Charlestown Boys & Girls Club (MA) Computer Clubhouse from 2001-2005.  I’m now the Knowledge Manager at the Intel Computer Clubhouse Network, at the Museum of Science, Boston.  I document local practice, train new coordinators & staff, manage the online community, the Village (a social network where youth members meet and post their digital media projects), and support local affiliate sustainability within the Network.
The Clubhouse learning approach is designed to empower youth from all backgrounds to become more capable, creative, and confident learners. This approach is grounded in research from the fields of education, developmental and social psychology, cognitive science, and youth development. It builds on research on the role of affect and motivation in the learning process, the importance of social context, and the interplay between individual and community development. It leverages new technologies to support new types of learning experiences and engage youth. Read more athttp://www.computerclubhouse.org/.
Most recently, as part of One Economy’s federal stimulus funded digital literacy initiative, I developed new strategies to scale up from 30 to over 100 afterschool Digital Connectors youth service programs nationally and managed social media campaigns publicly and internally with youth on ConnectorsClub.org.  I graduated as a Master in City Planning from MIT in Sept. ‘09, spending two years with the MIT@Lawrence university-community partnership and co-producing the documentary, Sustained City-Campus Engagement: Reflections on Our Practice.  Before MIT, I served as an AmeriCorps*VISTA at the Community Technology Centers VISTA Project at UMass Boston [later known as the Transmission Project].  In 2010, I piloted an afterschool program in Boston around conflict-transformation and photo-journalism with Peace In Focusand co-created a research group within MIT’s Center for Future Civic Media, the Department of Play, focused on the design of new mapping and mobile technology and methodologies to support youth as active participants in their communities.

Short Biography: (PS no paragraph formatting was taken over, so this looks like a long stream of wordiness - sorry!)

Karen Petersen-Kunigk received her Bachelor’s Teaching Degree in French and German and then taught French at the University of Utah while doing post-graduate work in Literature, Linguistics and Second Language Acquisition, resulting in a post-graduate TESOL certificate. This led her to Europe, where she was first introduced to the practicalities of Waldorf family home-life by catching frogs in the forest as a nanny with 3 little boys in Hannover, Lower Saxony, Germany.  
 
As a Fulbright Scholar, she spent the next year in Berlin, Germany, teaching in the John F. Kennedy School, a bi-lingual international school.  Then it was back to Hannover for a few years, teaching 2 week long intensive International Negotiation Techniques and Business English courses in convention centres and hotels. While attending local and international folk dances, she met more people involved in Waldorf communities, as well as her future husband.  

Karen began teaching at the Independent Waldorf School of Hannover/Maschsee in 1988, and completed the 3 year Waldorf Teacher Training (M. Ed. equiv.) program there in 1991, along with the official unlimited renewal Teaching Certificate. She also worked in Hannover as a translator.  When her son was three, her family moved to a national park and bird refuge: a little island in the North Sea, where cars are prohibited and the whole family cycled for 6 years. It was there that her daughter was born.  Two years later, they moved to Hessia, in central Germany, where she began teaching at the Independent Waldorf School of Diez/Lahn in Rheinland/Pfalz.   

Since 2006 her family has lived in the US, where she continues to enjoy what she left in Europe: playing cello for international folk and contra dances, as well as playing lute-guitar, hurdy-gurdy, medieval bagpipes and singing old French, German, Latin, English, Scottish, Irish and Swedish tales and ballads at Renaissance Fairs and Celtic Festivals.  Otherwise she enjoys reading and discussing books and history at family meal times with her husband and children.  When this is not possible she is knitting or spinning. 

She was very happy to be teaching German and Spanish in her first US Waldorf school in Tucson, Arizona until 2012 and loved being part of the unhurried, humane and holistic educational journey which allows more than one answer to be “correct. ”  That simply makes sense.  In the fall of 2012 she returned to Utah, where she is now bringing her many years of experience into hands-on enhancement and enrichment activities for students working on their world languages course in French, German, Spanish, Latin, Russian, Japanese and Chinese in a blended learning situation at a local charter school.
